1
00:00:12,054 --> 00:00:14,223
-Good evening.
-Good evening.

2
00:00:14,306 --> 00:00:16,934
<i>Terrace House</i> is a show about
six strangers, men and women,

3
00:00:17,017 --> 00:00:18,560
6 STRANGERS, MEN AND WOMEN,
SHARE A HOUSE.

4
00:00:18,644 --> 00:00:21,438
living together, and we observe
how they interact with each other.

5
00:00:21,521 --> 00:00:24,191
<i>All that we've prepared is</i>
<i>a beautiful home and automobile.</i>

6
00:00:24,274 --> 00:00:26,526
There is no script at all.

7
00:00:27,611 --> 00:00:29,738
First, Natsumi...

8
00:00:29,821 --> 00:00:31,990
or Princess Natsumi, is back from China.

9
00:00:33,033 --> 00:00:35,786
She's scared of her
after that last episode.

10
00:00:35,869 --> 00:00:36,870
It's okay.

11
00:00:36,954 --> 00:00:41,208
-Arman and Natsumi head to Enoshima.
-That's right.

12
00:00:41,291 --> 00:00:42,918
-They went.
-Yes, they went.

13
00:00:43,001 --> 00:00:45,128
You sound like you're reporting
the royal family news.

14
00:00:45,212 --> 00:00:47,214
"Princess Natsumi has visited Enoshima."

15
00:00:48,465 --> 00:00:49,549
About Arisa...

16
00:00:49,633 --> 00:00:51,176
ARMAN BITARAF, 25 YEARS OLD
NATSUMI SAITO, 26 YEARS OLD

17
00:00:51,260 --> 00:00:52,261
Do you really like her?

18
00:00:52,344 --> 00:00:54,596
Yeah, I do.

19
00:00:54,680 --> 00:00:56,932
I want to be in love, too.

20
00:00:57,015 --> 00:01:00,644
That could've been her making an appeal.

21
00:01:00,727 --> 00:01:02,563
But later on...

22
00:01:02,646 --> 00:01:05,857
-I went to Shonan.
-By yourself?

23
00:01:05,941 --> 00:01:07,442
MINORI NAKADA, 21 YEARS OLD
NATSUMI SAITO, 26 YEARS OLD

24
00:01:07,526 --> 00:01:08,527
Of course not!
With Arman.

25
00:01:08,610 --> 00:01:09,778
Why?

26
00:01:09,861 --> 00:01:12,239
-What do you mean?
-For fun?

27
00:01:12,322 --> 00:01:13,323
It's just sudden.

28
00:01:13,407 --> 00:01:15,367
-What? Sudden?
-What?

29
00:01:16,201 --> 00:01:19,162
It just sounds like you're mad at me.

30
00:01:19,246 --> 00:01:20,747
<i>They're both at fault.</i>

31
00:01:20,831 --> 00:01:21,873
It's an accumulation.

32
00:01:21,957 --> 00:01:23,500
If they got mad over one thing,

33
00:01:23,584 --> 00:01:26,086
then they could reason it out
how it happened and solve it.

34
00:01:26,169 --> 00:01:29,381
-But they're all intertwined.
-And from there...

35
00:01:29,464 --> 00:01:33,427
-The house meeting.
-That house meeting was scary.

36
00:01:34,469 --> 00:01:38,640
I didn't really like
the way Minori was talking to me.

37
00:01:38,724 --> 00:01:39,725
Her tone...

38
00:01:40,434 --> 00:01:43,186
Minori denied it,
saying that was not how she meant it.

39
00:01:43,270 --> 00:01:46,231
So that was me just honestly asking.

40
00:01:46,315 --> 00:01:49,067
But you kept taking it as criticism.

41
00:01:49,151 --> 00:01:51,028
You've just misunderstood each other.

42
00:01:51,111 --> 00:01:52,195
ARISA OHATA, 25 YEARS OLD

43
00:01:52,279 --> 00:01:54,364
So let's not let this happen again.

44
00:01:54,448 --> 00:01:55,991
Cheers!

45
00:01:56,825 --> 00:01:59,453
If you brush it off like that,

46
00:01:59,536 --> 00:02:01,580
the friendship
will always remain superficial.

47
00:02:01,663 --> 00:02:03,832
<i>This honest exchange of feelings,</i>

48
00:02:03,915 --> 00:02:07,085
you clearly see
this is how people build relationships.

49
00:02:07,169 --> 00:02:09,963
The current mood at <i>Terrace House</i>
is horrible.

50
00:02:10,047 --> 00:02:11,590
-Horrible.
-The worst!

51
00:02:11,673 --> 00:02:16,887
And the worst part was,
in the middle of the talk,

52
00:02:16,970 --> 00:02:19,348
when it was nonchalantly mentioned
that Arman still likes Arisa.

53
00:02:21,767 --> 00:02:23,935
So he told you why, right?

54
00:02:24,019 --> 00:02:27,898
That he likes Arisa,
and as a roommate, you'd help.

55
00:02:27,981 --> 00:02:30,734
You had that conversation, right?

56
00:02:30,817 --> 00:02:34,404
Wow, I wonder
where we're gonna start this episode?

57
00:02:34,488 --> 00:02:37,741
It'll be scary
if it's from the middle of the meeting.

58
00:02:39,368 --> 00:02:43,455
It's easy to say, "Okay, we're done."

59
00:02:43,538 --> 00:02:50,921
To figure out what went wrong or to say
who was at fault is the easy way out.

60
00:02:52,130 --> 00:02:55,467
If there's something you don't like,
no one will know if you don't speak up.

61
00:02:56,760 --> 00:03:00,722
But, like Minori, there are people
who just aren't that type.

62
00:03:00,806 --> 00:03:02,808
Which makes it difficult.

63
00:03:02,891 --> 00:03:07,229
But if something bothers you,

64
00:03:07,312 --> 00:03:10,649
I think it's better to say it
in any way you can.

65
00:03:10,732 --> 00:03:14,653
If we're going to live together,
it's better to voice it.

66
00:03:14,736 --> 00:03:17,614
Otherwise, what happened yesterday
will happen again.

67
00:03:17,697 --> 00:03:22,869
I think it's important to figure it out,
but it's a matter of personality.

68
00:03:22,953 --> 00:03:25,330
You're the type
who wants to get to the bottom of things.

69
00:03:25,414 --> 00:03:28,708
No, we're not just talking friendship.

70
00:03:29,626 --> 00:03:32,838
That's fine
if you're just hanging out for the day.

71
00:03:32,921 --> 00:03:35,340
But living together...

72
00:03:35,424 --> 00:03:38,593
Why don't you hear her out first,
and then respond.

73
00:03:38,677 --> 00:03:40,470
The same goes for you.

74
00:03:40,554 --> 00:03:42,472
You're interrupting me.

75
00:03:43,140 --> 00:03:45,892
Not everyone is like you.

76
00:03:45,976 --> 00:03:47,644
-I understand that.
-You do, right?

77
00:03:47,728 --> 00:03:50,689
-So Minori has her own personality.
-I know that, too.

78
00:03:50,772 --> 00:03:53,442
So I'm just asking you to hear her out.

79
00:03:53,525 --> 00:03:57,404
Minori wants it
to be phrased better, right?

80
00:03:57,487 --> 00:04:00,073
-But...
-Nacchan's words sound harsh to you.

81
00:04:00,157 --> 00:04:01,450
I don't mind that.

82
00:04:01,533 --> 00:04:03,994
And I'm not asking her to change.

83
00:04:04,077 --> 00:04:07,748
But the way you say things
can be controlled in that moment, right?

84
00:04:07,831 --> 00:04:10,459
As far as my personality goes,

85
00:04:10,542 --> 00:04:13,462
I don't think
the change is something to be forced.

86
00:04:13,545 --> 00:04:15,088
I just think, "Oh, well."

87
00:04:15,797 --> 00:04:19,301
There's no need to change yourself
for someone else.

88
00:04:19,384 --> 00:04:21,303
I think so, too.

89
00:04:21,386 --> 00:04:23,889
-Not yourself, just how you word things.
-How you say it.

90
00:04:23,972 --> 00:04:30,312
If we don't compromise a little,
there are some areas that won't work out.

91
00:04:30,395 --> 00:04:34,191
If we don't try to understand each other,

92
00:04:34,274 --> 00:04:36,318
this will happen again.

93
00:04:54,503 --> 00:04:57,506
TATSUYA UCHIHARA, 24 YEARS OLD,
HAIR STYLIST

94
00:04:57,589 --> 00:05:00,217
MINORI NAKADA, 21 YEARS OLD, MODEL

95
00:05:00,300 --> 00:05:03,136
ARMAN BITARAF, 25 YEARS OLD,
ASPIRING FIREFIGHTER

96
00:05:03,220 --> 00:05:06,348
ARISA OHATA, 25 YEARS OLD,
HAT DESIGNER

97
00:05:06,431 --> 00:05:09,559
HIKARU OTA, 18 YEARS OLD,
MODEL, CONSTRUCTION WORKER

98
00:05:09,643 --> 00:05:13,104
NATSUMI SAITO, 26 YEARS OLD,
MODEL, ASPIRING ACTRESS

99
00:05:20,529 --> 00:05:23,448
MISHUKU, TOKYO

100
00:05:23,532 --> 00:05:26,451
SHABU SHABU ONYASAI

101
00:05:26,535 --> 00:05:29,746
You made that "don" thing, right?

102
00:05:29,830 --> 00:05:31,122
The poke don?

103
00:05:31,206 --> 00:05:32,833
How did Arisa like it?

104
00:05:32,916 --> 00:05:34,167
She said it was good.

105
00:05:35,961 --> 00:05:39,673
I wish it hadn't been
under those circumstances.

106
00:05:39,756 --> 00:05:41,049
That's true.

107
00:05:41,967 --> 00:05:44,761
-You told her your feelings though, right?
-I did.

108
00:05:44,844 --> 00:05:46,471
Why don't you tell her again?

109
00:05:47,222 --> 00:05:49,516
I do want to ask her.

110
00:05:49,599 --> 00:05:54,396
The next time I ask her out for dinner,
I'll ask how she really feels about me.

111
00:05:55,063 --> 00:05:57,732
-The feelings are there, I think.
-Seriously?

112
00:05:57,816 --> 00:05:59,734
-Yeah.
-Yeah, for real.

113
00:05:59,818 --> 00:06:02,237
Why don't you go on a date with someone?

114
00:06:02,320 --> 00:06:05,782
Either way, there has to be
more conversation.

115
00:06:05,865 --> 00:06:08,827
But I guess going out to eat would work.

116
00:06:08,910 --> 00:06:12,289
A date is
a way to get to know them, right?

117
00:06:12,372 --> 00:06:14,124
That's true.

118
00:06:15,125 --> 00:06:17,002
What about the fireman thing?

119
00:06:17,085 --> 00:06:19,296
Or work, I mean...

120
00:06:19,379 --> 00:06:21,715
I don't have anything
from the place in Kamakura right now.

121
00:06:21,798 --> 00:06:23,300
Wanna come work at my place?

122
00:06:24,217 --> 00:06:25,594
The construction company.

123
00:06:25,677 --> 00:06:26,803
I can work with you?

124
00:06:26,886 --> 00:06:28,138
-Yeah.
-Seriously?

125
00:06:28,221 --> 00:06:30,056
-Yeah, together.
-Like Tom Sawyer?

126
00:06:30,140 --> 00:06:31,182
Yeah.

127
00:06:31,266 --> 00:06:33,143
-Sounds good.
-Yeah. It'll be fun.

128
00:06:33,810 --> 00:06:36,938
It'll start either this week or next week.

129
00:06:37,022 --> 00:06:39,482
-The project in Nakano.
-For real? Then...

130
00:06:39,566 --> 00:06:41,651
-You'll do it?
-Will you ask for me?

131
00:06:41,735 --> 00:06:43,862
-You'll come?
-Yeah.

132
00:06:43,945 --> 00:06:45,572
I'll lend you the outfit then.

133
00:06:45,655 --> 00:06:48,617
It'll be fun working with you.

134
00:06:57,208 --> 00:07:00,128
This is the first time the three of us
are having breakfast together.

135
00:07:01,588 --> 00:07:03,465
We're never home.

136
00:07:04,090 --> 00:07:06,217
We all have different schedules.

137
00:07:07,677 --> 00:07:09,554
-You're both off today?
-Yes.

138
00:07:10,138 --> 00:07:12,223
No, I've got to go to Aoyama for 4:00 p.m.

139
00:07:12,307 --> 00:07:14,267
Oh, your audition.

140
00:07:22,359 --> 00:07:24,402
Thanks for the food, Minori.

141
00:07:24,486 --> 00:07:25,654
Thank you.

142
00:07:25,737 --> 00:07:26,738
Of course.

143
00:07:29,824 --> 00:07:31,743
-Thanks for the food.
-Sure.

144
00:07:32,994 --> 00:07:34,704
It was delicious.

145
00:07:39,668 --> 00:07:40,877
What's this?

146
00:07:42,754 --> 00:07:44,547
This here, what is it?

147
00:07:44,631 --> 00:07:45,632
Oh, it's meat.

148
00:07:45,715 --> 00:07:47,759
-Meat?
-Uchi got it as a gift.

149
00:07:47,842 --> 00:07:50,303
-Wow.
-Huge steaks.

150
00:07:51,012 --> 00:07:52,847
It's in a wooden box.

151
00:07:54,057 --> 00:07:56,434
Oh, wow! Look at this!

152
00:07:56,518 --> 00:07:57,686
Amazing, right?

153
00:07:57,769 --> 00:07:59,479
-Wow!
-Oh, it's Hidagyu.

154
00:07:59,562 --> 00:08:01,648
I don't know how to cook it.

155
00:08:02,315 --> 00:08:05,026
Just salt and pepper would be
probably enough for this.

156
00:08:05,652 --> 00:08:07,821
-That's true.
-Wow.

157
00:08:07,904 --> 00:08:10,907
-Maybe cooked medium...
-Yeah.

158
00:08:10,991 --> 00:08:13,994
-Or even rare.
-That's true.

159
00:08:14,077 --> 00:08:16,037
-Wow.
-Wow, Uchi.

160
00:08:18,039 --> 00:08:20,542
-I'm going now.
-Bye.

161
00:08:20,625 --> 00:08:22,210
Thanks for the food.

162
00:08:39,728 --> 00:08:43,606
I just heard today that Minori's leaving.

163
00:08:45,358 --> 00:08:46,860
At the end of February.

164
00:08:46,943 --> 00:08:50,238
-What? When did she say that?
-I just heard today.

165
00:08:50,321 --> 00:08:53,283
She's going to leave
when she graduates university.

166
00:08:53,992 --> 00:08:56,536
Are they related somehow?

167
00:08:56,619 --> 00:08:58,079
Not really.

168
00:08:59,456 --> 00:09:01,958
-It's good timing?
-Yeah.

169
00:09:02,042 --> 00:09:04,419
What'll you do when Minori leaves?

170
00:09:04,502 --> 00:09:06,421
I'd probably leave then, too.

171
00:09:07,297 --> 00:09:10,884
If you do, would you get an apartment
and live together?

172
00:09:11,801 --> 00:09:13,928
I don't know yet.

173
00:09:14,012 --> 00:09:15,472
I might live on my own.

174
00:09:16,347 --> 00:09:19,184
When you have different priorities...

175
00:09:19,267 --> 00:09:23,063
-You have different priorities?
-Yeah.

176
00:09:23,146 --> 00:09:26,858
Well, our views towards work
are different.

177
00:09:27,609 --> 00:09:31,029
I want to work hard right now.

178
00:09:31,988 --> 00:09:37,660
She's fine with minimal finances
as long as she can have a normal life.

179
00:09:38,578 --> 00:09:40,288
Kind of like that.

180
00:09:40,371 --> 00:09:42,874
It would've been great
if we were just friends.

181
00:09:42,957 --> 00:09:44,959
But if we're going to be
in a relationship...

182
00:09:46,086 --> 00:09:47,253
then I think...

183
00:09:48,171 --> 00:09:50,215
we should have similar goals.

184
00:09:50,298 --> 00:09:53,218
Yeah, you could motivate each other.

185
00:09:53,301 --> 00:09:59,891
At first, she quit her other job
and said she'd focus on her modelling.

186
00:10:00,809 --> 00:10:04,312
But lately she's either just at home
or going out.

187
00:10:05,271 --> 00:10:06,773
I've been...

188
00:10:07,690 --> 00:10:10,443
a little concerned about that lately.

189
00:10:10,527 --> 00:10:12,195
We've talked about it before,

190
00:10:12,278 --> 00:10:15,907
but she just says
she knows what she's doing.

191
00:10:15,990 --> 00:10:17,492
She's just living off modeling, right?

192
00:10:17,575 --> 00:10:18,993
-Yeah.
-Or is she?

193
00:10:19,077 --> 00:10:22,080
She said she can get by.

194
00:10:22,163 --> 00:10:24,958
-So then she's here when she's off.
-I can't get by with just modeling.

195
00:10:25,041 --> 00:10:27,544
On her computer or watching TV...

196
00:10:27,627 --> 00:10:29,337
And she says she's...

197
00:10:29,420 --> 00:10:31,089
perfectly happy doing that.

198
00:10:32,132 --> 00:10:34,342
That's fine if that's the case.

199
00:10:37,095 --> 00:10:38,596
Oh, it's Nacchan.

200
00:10:39,139 --> 00:10:40,932
-Who'd you think it was?
-You couldn't tell?

201
00:10:41,015 --> 00:10:43,977
-You have bad vision?
-No, it's 20/20.

202
00:10:44,060 --> 00:10:45,687
20/20 and you couldn't tell?

203
00:10:45,770 --> 00:10:48,648
-20/20 is pretty good.
-It's perfect.

204
00:10:48,731 --> 00:10:50,066
Oh, yeah.

205
00:10:51,651 --> 00:10:53,945
-Long time no see.
-Long time no see.

206
00:10:54,028 --> 00:10:57,448
The three of us had breakfast
for the first time this morning.

207
00:10:57,532 --> 00:10:59,784
-Well, more like lunch...
-Which three?

208
00:10:59,868 --> 00:11:01,536
Minori and Asari, not Asari...

209
00:11:01,619 --> 00:11:03,872
Asari? That's bad.

210
00:11:05,373 --> 00:11:06,833
I meant Arisa.

211
00:11:06,916 --> 00:11:09,627
What do you girls talk about?

212
00:11:10,211 --> 00:11:11,963
It's light stuff.

213
00:11:12,881 --> 00:11:17,385
-We avoid mentioning the other day.
-I see.

214
00:11:17,468 --> 00:11:18,970
-Minori's home, right?
-Yeah.

215
00:11:20,221 --> 00:11:21,848
Do the two of you talk?

216
00:11:22,974 --> 00:11:24,976
Not really.

217
00:11:25,059 --> 00:11:26,144
You don't get along?

218
00:11:26,227 --> 00:11:28,897
-We're not close.
-Well, you're probably just different.

219
00:11:29,981 --> 00:11:32,400
Do you know about Minori?

220
00:11:32,483 --> 00:11:34,444
-That she's leaving?
-Yeah.

221
00:11:34,527 --> 00:11:36,404
So, before then...

222
00:11:37,071 --> 00:11:39,532
I'd like for our relationship to change.

223
00:11:55,882 --> 00:11:57,425
You scared me.

224
00:11:59,510 --> 00:12:01,554
-Going to sleep?
-No.

225
00:12:01,638 --> 00:12:03,723
-I wanted to talk.
-About?

226
00:12:03,806 --> 00:12:05,683
You said you're leaving, right?

227
00:12:05,767 --> 00:12:09,729
-So I am going to leave, too...
-Together?

228
00:12:09,812 --> 00:12:11,648
Yeah, at the same time.

229
00:12:12,607 --> 00:12:14,192
-End of February, is it?
-Yeah.

230
00:12:14,275 --> 00:12:17,236
End of February.

231
00:12:18,196 --> 00:12:22,700
Does it need to be timed with your school?

232
00:12:22,784 --> 00:12:24,577
There's a month left.

233
00:12:24,661 --> 00:12:29,874
If there's no merit being here...

234
00:12:29,958 --> 00:12:34,212
I thought maybe I could only enjoy this
while I was still a student.

235
00:12:34,295 --> 00:12:36,005
That's...

236
00:12:37,423 --> 00:12:39,467
-Not right?
-Yeah, maybe not.

237
00:12:39,550 --> 00:12:40,927
What's not right about it?

238
00:12:41,010 --> 00:12:42,804
I thought maybe...

239
00:12:43,721 --> 00:12:46,933
it'd be good to have
some kind of goal here...

240
00:12:47,016 --> 00:12:50,561
so that it would benefit you.

241
00:12:51,813 --> 00:12:57,110
But to just rely on this environment
or to just live easy feels wrong.

242
00:12:57,193 --> 00:12:59,529
What do you want me to do?

243
00:12:59,612 --> 00:13:02,865
-You want me to just leave?
-I'm not sure.

244
00:13:02,949 --> 00:13:06,536
But I don't want you
to just pass time here.

245
00:13:06,619 --> 00:13:12,500
I'm not here just because it's fun,
and I'm not just lying around.

246
00:13:13,292 --> 00:13:14,752
How are things with Nacchan?

247
00:13:15,628 --> 00:13:18,006
-It's awkward.
-Right?

248
00:13:18,089 --> 00:13:22,427
You're used to withdrawing
and just giving up.

249
